***CONTENT
From May 19th to 23rd, the Chelsea Flower Show will once again be packed full of local gardening enthusiasts and day-trippers from further afield. If, like us, you would rather eat flowers than look at them – you’re in luck! The pink flowers on the map below indicate restaurants in the surrounding area that are offering floral-themed menus and creative cocktails. If you’re just looking for somewhere good to eat nearby, the little daffodils highlight some reliable local favourites. View Eat Out: Chelsea Flower Show in a larger map Daphne’s – The Chelsea Flower Show menu is priced at £22.50 for two courses and £26.50 for three. Dishes include deep-fried courgette flowers with mozzarella and tomato salsa; chargrilled chicken breast with peas, broad beans and pancetta; and elderflower jelly with strawberry ripple ice-cream. Brompton Quarter Café – From 3pm to 5pm, the café is serving a Luxury Floral Tea including homemade sandwiches garnished with edible flowers, warm scones and their signature flower Danish pastry. With a pot of flower tea or a refreshing still lemonade, it will set you back £14.95 per head. (Alternatively, pop in earlier for their ‘La Vie En Rose’ set lunch menu). Ghost Inc – One of South Ken’s hottest bars will be adding edible pansies to alcoholic creations like their limited edition Chelsea Flower cocktail – a blend of elderflower-infused vodka, rhubarb, sugar syrup, lemon juice and Perrier Jouet champagne. Delicious! The Cinnamon Club – Chef Vivek Singh’s floral menu (£60) starts with a hibiscus and rose petal bellini and finishes with a rose petal and milk carom seed crumble. In between, there are crisp zucchini flowers with pomegranate raita; grilled aubergine with citrus morel and saffron sauce; and asparagus spears with kadhai spices. The Botanist – If you’re near Sloane Square, pop into the ever-popular Botanist and try the Lavender Bloom cocktail (honey and apricot liqueur and Champagne muddled with fresh lavender) or a Jasmine Blossom (mandarin-infused vodka, Champagne and jasmine syrup). Le Cercle – The floral menu is priced between £17 and £37 depending on the number of courses and matching wines you go for. Dishes include violet scented coley; a spring salad with rose petal vinaigrette; and a lavender crème brulee with apricot. Roussillon – Chef Alexis Gauthier is well known for his elegant vegetarian menus and this year’s Flower Show menu is no exception. Priced at £65, it’s not cheap but features culinary show-stoppers like the open ravioli of purple and green watercress and a deliciously light chrysanthemum soufflé. Harvey Nichols Fifth Floor Restaurant – The restaurant is serving traditional afternoon tea between 2.30pm and 5pm to celebrate the launch of the new garden-inspired fragrance by Laura Mercier. In the bar, cocktail aficionados can sip floral-themed creations like the ‘London in Bloom Martini’ – an elegant blend of gin, orange flower water, fresh rhubarb and lychee, topped with lavender sugar.
