***TITLE
Get Your Claws Out For Trishna's Week-Long Crab Festival
***AUTHOR
city-eating
***DATE
2009-03-04 14:55:00
***CONTENT
From Monday 9th to Sunday 15th March, Trishna in Marylebone is hosting their inaugural Crab Festival. The week-long celebration is a tribute to the original Trishna restaurant in Mumbai which is famous for its seafood dishes, including the signature whole crab with butter, black pepper and garlic. The London outpost will be serving a wide range of crab dishes, inspired by Indian coastal cuisine and created by head chef Ravi Deulkar, who previously worked at the Michelin-starred Rasoi Vineet Bhatia in Chelsea. He has built up an impressive network of British seafood suppliers for the occasion and will cooking Cornish brown crab, spider crab, snow crab, Norwegian king crab and blue swimmer crab throughout the week. “We’re proud to follow our Mumbai counterpart’s lead by putting crab at the heart of our menu,” explains Ravi, “We thought it would be fun to celebrate this wonderful ingredient in all its different guises with our own festival. It’s a bit of fun for our customers and it’s a brilliant culinary challenge for the kitchen. We’re going to be coming up with some amazing new dishes that may end up on the menu long term.” The special crab menu will include dishes such as shellfish rasam; blue swimmer crab and white lentil cake; and Tandoori king crab with ginger kachumber. There will be seafood-themed events throughout the week including wine tastings, a ‘crab-cracking’ class, and a competition of ‘Guess the weight of the king crab’ to win a free meal for two. If you’re not a big fan of crustacea, why not pop in on Sunday to try out their new brunch menu? Priced at £12.75, diners begin with traditional ‘Rasam’ – a South Indian soup made with yellow lentils, tamarind juice, tomatoes and pepper – and then choose an Indian-inspired main dish. The menu includes scrambled eggs with sigri smoked salmon; seafood biriyani; Goan sausage hot dogs with mustard chutney; and fresh green lentil and fennel stuffed with homemade masala paneer. A traditional drink is also included in this set price: either one of three different lassi flavours – mango, salt or roasted cumin – or a bloody Mary infused with either tamarind or horseradish. Children under six eat free so why not take your little curry lovers along too?
