The Talbot Inn, Ripley has just reopened after a massive Merchant Inns Ltd. refit that has seen this 15th Century inn keep all its original charm of low, head-splitting, beams and cosy inglenook fires but now also benefit from very modern facilities. The 400 year old oak main staircase looks like it’s been in quite a few wars and it’s odd to think that Admiral Nelson, who frequently stayed here en route to Portsmouth, must have run his hand where you now run yours. When he wasn’t running his hand over Emma that is. A new restaurant with a cool copper ceiling and carved from an adjoining building blends classical and modern décor with a shiny conservatory while the menu is modern and assured from Chef Ian Richards. Upstairs in the original building are stunning, romantic bedrooms while out back are tasteful new rooms in a purpose built building that blends in with the original structure well. A pub and restaurant for locals and a hotel that’s ideal for corporates in the week and couples at the weekend, The Talbot is a warm place to go this autumn and just a short ride out of London. With RHS Wisley next door, you can combine a trip with some shopping for tasteful Xmas gifts too. Kiss me Hardy!
