People in Marlow must be fed up with being told their home is the new Ludlow. It’s probably rather confusing for the postman too. The comparison is made because there are so many fine restaurants in this bijou little town just forty minutes or so from London: The Oak Room in Danesfield House, The Hand & Flowers, The Vanilla Pod and opening now, Aubergine at the Compleat Angler housed in a historic 400 year old building. William Drabble has been head chef of the London Aubergine for ten years and is now Executive Chef of both restaurants and on this party night he is out mingling in his whites, while back in the large kitchen his lads and lasses are turning out canapés like there’s no tomorrow. And from the amount of champagne we are all drinking there may well be no tomorrow, at least not one that’s free of paracetemol. The large figure of Tom Kerridge - owner and chef of local legend The Hand & Flowers, together with his wife Beth who does so much to make their restaurant so welcoming - is here cheerfully consuming the quality nibbles, his giant hands making them look like kid’s treats. He’s affable and very complimentary about William and also about Adam Simmonds, Head Chef up the road at the Oak Room. He seems genuinely pleased that with Aubergine, another fine restaurant, is opening and sees it as being good for the area. Other chefs are in the room, including Laurent Michel from L’Oranger, another part of the London Fine Dining Group, and with him are his ebullient Maitre d’ Eric and their patisserie chef. It’s a ‘compleat’ works outing for them. Local people seem well heeled and perhaps slightly older than you might expect, but exactly the sort of reliable, regular, diner the restaurant is no doubt looking for. As the one-man band lurches into another timeless Tony Bennet classic, we pop outside for a fag and to admire the restaurant’s gorgeous location next to the Thames and Marlow’s lovely old bridge. William’s menu promises great things and it’s arguable that the country is where affordable good food will be found as London rates, and a reduction in consumer spending power, start to bite. The Aubergine should make leaving London for a weekend break more attractive than ever
