***TITLE
New and Notable Openings: London
***AUTHOR
city-eating
***DATE
2008-09-19 16:10:00
***CONTENT
Tierra Brindisa - London’s tapas fans no longer have to trek to Borough Market for their fix, as the team behind the infamous Tapas Brindisa have opened Tierra Brindisa in Soho. The menu includes some great cheese boards and a comprehensive Spanish wine list, as well as familiar favourites like Padron peppers and Iberian ham. Unlike the original, you can book tables here so queueing is a thing of the past. No reviews yet so get yourselves down there and start scribbling!Min Jiang - With its location on the tenth floor of Kensington’s Royal Garden Hotel, Min Jiang boasts a great view and a sophisticated Chinese menu featuring their signature Bejing duck dish, served as three separate but equally delicious courses. Our users say that ‘the food is stunning and just as good as the Singapore restaurant’ and there are good reports on the bar and service too. It's 'a bit pricey' but it sounds like it's worth a visit.Buddha Bar - Despite having conquered Paris and Dubai, Buddha Bar is failing to impress london-eating’s users. Diners have complained that although ‘the place looks amazing’, the pan-Asian menu ‘wasn’t very inventive’ and the staff were ‘rude’. It’s still early days though so Buddha Bar has time to iron out the creases and up their game.We’ve also been busy adding local gems recommended by our users. Here are some of the best:Richard Phillips at Chapel Down in Kent - \"I was amazed at how smoothly everything was running the staff was friendly and attentive and the food was exquisite. Something that came as a pleasant surprise was the size of the portions. Often with fine dining I have left a restaurant - though pleased with the taste, aroma and presentation - feeling hungry. Surely the point of any dining experience is to be served excellent food in the right quantity and I was very pleased to say that the portions at Richard Phillips are generous.\"L’Esperance in Surbiton - “L'Esperance is my favourite restaurant in the Surbiton area, both for visits as a couple and with the entire family. The menu is a mixture of standard and slightly more adventurous French dishes. The food is consistently well cooked and nicely presented and lives up to the management's claim always to use fresh ingredients. Recommended for pretty much any occasion.”If we’re missing your local favourite, let us know. Send us an email via the Contact Us page, here
